{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-99fd818c3f743db7", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tSpEmoC: A Balanced Speaker-Segment\n2\tMultimodal Emotion Benchmark\n3\tSania Bano1 , Shahzad Ahmad2 , Santosh Kumar Vipparthi1 , Sukalpa\n4\tChanda2 , and Subrahmanyam Murala3\n5\t\n6\tarXiv:2607.18109v1 [cs.CV] 20 Jul 2026\n7\t\n8\t1\n9\t\n10\tCVPR Lab, Indian Institute of Technology Ropar, India\n11\t2\n12\tØstfold University College, Norway\n13\t3\n14\tCVPR Lab, SCSS, Trinity College Dublin, Ireland\n15\tsania.22eez0012@iitrpr.ac.in\n16\t\n17\tFig. 1: Overview of SpEmoC construction and evaluation. Multimodal filtering and\n18\texpert validation refine 306K speaking clips into 30K balanced clips across seven emotions for diverse benchmarking.\n19\tAbstract. Understanding human emotions in spoken conversations is\n20\ta key challenge in affective computing, with applications in empathetic\n21\tAI, human computer interaction, and mental health monitoring. However, existing datasets vary in scale, emotion distribution, modality alignment, and data partitioning strategies, which can influence reliable crossdataset generalization and minority-emotion modeling. We introduce\n22\tSpEmoC a Speaking segment Emotion for Conversations comprising\n23\t306,544 raw clips from 3,100 English language movies and TV series.\n24\tFrom these, 30,000 high quality, class balanced clips are curated, featuring synchronized visual, audio, and textual modalities annotated for\n25\tseven emotions through a hybrid pipeline that integrates pretrained models with human validation. SpEmoC uses strict movie- and series-level\n26\tsplits to prevent content overlap between split sets, allowing more reliable\n27\tevaluation of model generalization. The dataset also maintains a nearbalanced distribution across seven emotions, including minority classes\n28\tsuch as Fear and Disgust, which supports more balanced learning across\n29\tcategories. Extensive experiments, including in-domain benchmarking,\n30\tcross-dataset transfer, low-data training, class-imbalance analysis, and\n31\tmodality transfer show that balanced data and careful splitting lead to\n32\tmore stable performance across emotions when models are evaluated on\n33\tother datasets. These results highlight the importance of dataset design\n34\tfor robust and transferable multimodal emotion recognition.\n35\tProject Page: The full dataset is available at the following link\n36\t\n37\t\f2\n38\t\n39\tS. Bano et al.\n40\tKeywords: Multimodal Dataset · Cross-Dataset Generalization · Class\n41\tImbalance · Audio-Text Fusion\n42\t\n43\t1\n44\t\n45\tIntroduction\n46\t\n47\tUnderstanding emotions in spoken conversations is central to affective computing, with applications in empathetic AI, mental health monitoring, pain detection [16], and human computer interaction [18]. Emotion is inherently multimodal expressed through facial expressions, vocal prosody, and linguistic context yet robust multimodal modeling in natural conversations remains a major challenge. While modern multimodal models have advanced rapidly, robust\n48\temotion recognition in natural conversational settings remains fundamentally\n49\tconstrained by benchmark design. The structure of the dataset, including how\n50\tclips are segmented, class distribution, and the partitioning strategy, directly\n51\tinfluences generalization stability and performance on minority emotions.\n52\tMultimodal Emotion Recognition (MER) faces significant challenges that\n53\thinder its deployment in dynamic, dialogue-driven contexts. Most existing benchmarks focus on unimodal settings, such as facial expressions [14, 29] or audio [6, 23]. They suffer from limited modality alignment and annotation scale\n54\t[1, 19, 28]. Datasets like the Multimodal EmotionLines Dataset (MELD) [20],\n55\twith 13,000 utterances from the TV series Friends, and CAER [13], which includes 13,201 video clips from 79 TV shows with audio and visual tracks, offer multimodal annotations at limited scales. Similarly, EmoWOZ [8] provides\n56\t11,000+ task-oriented dialogue utterances with multimodal labels. However,\n57\tthese datasets are constrained by relatively small sizes and imbalanced emotion\n58\tdistributions, with MELD and CAER dominated by \"Neutral\" emotions and\n59\tunderrepresentation of \"Fear\" and \"Disgust\" (see Figure 2(a)). These datasets\n60\tlack real-world diversity and, being built from TV series, often reuse characters\n61\tacross splits, making test sets not truly unseen. Similarly, the M3ED dataset [31]\n62\toffers 9,000 utterances from TV series but falls short in capturing the breadth\n63\tof emotional expressions needed for generalization. Furthermore, the reliance\n64\ton expensive human annotations and the absence of synchronized multimodal\n65\talignment limit the scalability and applicability of these datasets. Fusing heterogeneous modalities also remains challenging due to differences in data representation, temporal dynamics, and emotional relevance across text, audio, and\n66\tvisual streams [27, 28].\n67\tTo address these limitations, we introduce SpEmoC, a large-scale Speakingsegment Emotion for Conversations dataset constructed from diverse movies\n68\tand TV series. SpEmoC provides synchronized video, audio, and text modalities, focusing on natural speaking segments that convey explicit emotional intent\n69\tunder varied real-world conditions. A hybrid annotation framework integrates\n70\tpretrained text and speech models with human validation to ensure accurate\n71\tand balanced labeling across seven emotion categories.\n72\tTo comprehensively evaluate the dataset, we benchmark several state-of-theart multimodal emotion recognition models on SpEmoC and conduct extensive\n73\t\n74\t\fSpEmoC: A Balanced Speaker-Segment Multimodal Emotion Benchmark\n75\tMELD\n76\tTrain (9989)\n77\tFear 2.7%\n78\t\n79\tDisgust 2.7%\n80\t\n81\tJoy 17.4%\n82\t\n83\tMELD\n84\tVal (1109)\n85\tFear 3.6%\n86\t\n87\tDisgust 2.0%\n88\t\n89\tJoy 14.7%\n90\tAnger 13.8%\n91\tNeutral 42.4%\n92\t\n93\tSurprise 12.1%\n94\tSadness 6.8%\n95\t\n96\tCAER\n97\tTrain (9222)\n98\tFear 3.9%\n99\t\n100\tDisgust 5.4%\n101\t\n102\tJoy 20.7%\n103\t\n104\tSurprise 13.5%\n105\tSadness 10.0%\n106\t\n107\tCAER\n108\tVal (1316)\n109\tFear 3.9%\n110\t\n111\tDisgust 5.4%\n112\t\n113\tSpEmoC\n114\tTrain (21407)\n115\tFear 11.1%\n116\tDisgust 23.1%\n117\t\n118\tJoy 11.7%\n119\t\n120\tSurprise 11.9%\n121\tSadness 11.1%\n122\t\n123\tSpEmoC\n124\tVal (2400)\n125\tFear 9.4%\n126\t\n127\tDisgust 23.0%\n128\t\n129\tSadness\n130\t\n131\tAnger 12.3%\n132\t\n133\t72.2\n134\t66.0\n135\t60.551.7\n136\t48.5\n137\t\n138\t36.0\n139\t\n140\t52.6\n141\t47.1\n142\t41.3\n143\t\n144\tSpEmoC\n145\tTest (6056)\n146\tFear 12.0%\n147\t\n148\tDisgust 21.4%\n149\t\n150\tAnger 16.3%\n151\tNeutral 13.3%\n152\t\n153\tAnger 21.0%\n154\tNeutral 14.8%\n155\t\n156\tSurprise 15.7%\n157\tSadness 8.1%\n158\t\n159\t(a)\n160\t\n161\t61.0 75.5 Neutral\n162\t\n163\t31.8\n164\t32.4\n165\t35.1\n166\t\n167\tSurprise 11.9%\n168\tSadness 11.1%\n169\t\n170\tJoy 9.5%\n171\t\n172\tAnger 18.6%\n173\tSurprise 14.9%\n174\tSadness 7.5%\n175\t\n176\tDisgust 5.5%\n177\t\n178\tSurprise\n179\t\n180\t80.9\n181\t74.4\n182\t\n183\tNeutral 34.7%\n184\t\n185\tJoy 14.2%\n186\t\n187\tNeutral 13.1%\n188\t\n189\tCAER\n190\tTest (2640)\n191\tFear 3.9%\n192\t\n193\tAnger 12.3%\n194\tNeutral 34.7%\n195\t\n196\t71.1\n197\t66.4\n198\t60.1\n199\t50.5\n200\t\n201\tSurprise 10.8%\n202\tSadness 8.0%\n203\t\n204\tJoy 20.6%\n205\t\n206\tAnger 12.3%\n207\tSurprise 11.9%\n208\tSadness 11.1%\n209\t\n210\tFear\n211\t\n212\tAnger 13.2%\n213\tNeutral 48.1%\n214\t\n215\tJoy 20.7%\n216\t\n217\tNeutral 34.7%\n218\t\n219\tMuIT\n220\tMISA\n221\tEmotionCLIP\n222\tTCL-MAP\n223\tEMOE\n224\t\n225\tDisgust 2.6%\n226\t\n227\tJoy 15.4%\n228\t\n229\tAnger 11.1%\n230\tNeutral 47.2%\n231\t\n232\tMELD\n233\tTest (2610)\n234\tFear 1.9%\n235\t\n236\t3\n237\t\n238\tSurprise 13.4%\n239\tSadness 7.8%\n240\t\n241\t66.4\n242\t75.366.9\n243\t75.5\n244\t\n245\tJoy84.7\n246\t\n247\t50.9\n248\t51.6\n249\t60.1\n250\t65.8\n251\t73.8\n252\t\n253\t49.8\n254\t55.8\n255\t60.0\n256\t66.8\n257\t70.8\n258\t\n259\tAnger\n260\t\n261\tDisgust\n262\t\n263\t(b)\n264\t\n265\tFig. 2: (a) Emotion class distribution across train, validation, and test splits for SpEmoC, MELD [20], and CAER [13]. SpEmoC exhibits a more balanced distribution\n266\tacross all seven emotions, while MELD and CAER are dominated by the Neutral class.\n267\t(b) Class-wise baseline performance on SpEmoC, showing more consistent F1-scores\n268\tdue to the balanced emotion distribution.\n269\t\n270\tcross-dataset evaluations on MELD and CAER. These experiments demonstrate\n271\tthat balanced supervision yields more stable and transferable performance across\n272\temotion categories, particularly for previously underrepresented classes. In addition, we perform detailed ablation studies including low-data regimes, crossdataset fine-tuning, neutral-class removal, and unimodal versus multimodal analysis to validate the robustness and practical utility of SpEmoC for real-world\n273\tmultimodal emotion understanding. The contributions of the paper are as follows:\n274\t– A large scale, class balanced dataset of speaking segment clips with tightly\n275\taligned visual, auditory, and linguistic modalities.\n276\t– A scalable multimodal annotation pipeline integrating pretrained text and\n277\tspeech models with human validation to ensure synchronized alignment and\n278\thigh-quality emotion labeling.\n279\t– Through cross-dataset evaluations on MELD and CAER with multiple SOTA\n280\tmodels, we show that SpEmoC enables more balanced class-wise performance and improved robustness to class imbalance, particularly for minority\n281\temotions.\n282\t– We provide a comprehensive empirical study of multimodal generalization,\n283\tincluding low-resource settings, neutral-class analysis, and unimodal versus\n284\tmultimodal comparisons, offering insights into benchmark design for robust\n285\taffective modeling.\n286\tSpEmoC advances multimodal emotion recognition through larger scale, balanced classes, and speaking-segment alignment, providing a stable and transferable benchmark for affect modeling.\n287\t\n288\t\f4\n289\t\n290\tS. Bano et al.\n291\t\n292\t2\n293\t\n294\tRelated Work\n295\t\n296\tEmotion Datasets: Early affective computing studies relied on acted or studiocontrolled corpora such as IEMOCAP [3], RAVDESS [15], and EmoReact [17],\n297\twhich offered limited expressive diversity and small emotional vocabularies.\n298\tLater multimodal datasets integrated video, audio, and text for conversational\n299\temotion analysis. MELD [20] and CAER [13] expanded to TV-series dialogues\n300\tbut remain small (< 14k samples) and heavily skewed toward neutral expressions. CMU-MOSEI [28] covers monologue-based content, while M3ED [31] and\n301\tEmoWOZ [8] provide task-oriented or synthetic dialogues. Recent large-scale\n302\tefforts such as EmotionTalk [24], EMOVOME [10], and EmotionCLIP [30] improve coverage through weak supervision or multilingual expansion but still lack\n303\tbalanced, human-validated, temporally aligned annotations. EmotionLLAMA’s\n304\tMERR [4] includes 28,618 coarse- and 4,487 fine-grained samples, many from\n305\tnon-English dubbed videos. A concise comparison in Table 1 highlights these\n306\tlimitations and motivates the design of SpEmoC as a fair, large-scale, and\n307\tculturally diverse benchmark.\n308\tModel-Level Advances: Multimodal emotion recognition models have evolved\n309\tfrom early feature fusion methods to attention-based and contrastive learning\n310\tframeworks. Transformer-based architectures such as MulT [25] and MISA [11]\n311\tmodel cross-modal interactions between text, audio, and visual streams, while\n312\trecent approaches including TCL-MAP [32] and EMOE [7] further improve multimodal fusion and representation learning. EmotionCLIP [30] leverages visionlanguage contrastive pretraining to align emotional semantics across modalities.\n313\tDespite these advances, model performance remains strongly dependent on the\n314\tquality and balance of available datasets, which motivates the development of\n315\tmore robust multimodal benchmarks such as SpEmoC.\n316\tTable 1: Comparison with existing multimodal emotion recognition datasets. Modalities: A = Audio, V = Visual, T = Text.\n317\tDataset\n318\t\n319\t#Clips\n320\t\n321\tModalities\n322\t\n323\t#Emotions\n324\t\n325\tSource\n326\t\n327\tIEMOCAP [3]\n328\tCMU-MOSEI [28]\n329\tMELD [20]\n330\tCAER [13]\n331\tRAVDESS [15]\n332\tEmoReact [17]\n333\t\n334\t10k\n335\t23k\n336\t13k\n337\t13k\n338\t7k\n339\t1k\n340\t\n341\tV, A, T\n342\tV, A, T\n343\tV, A, T\n344\tV, A\n345\tV, A\n346\tV, A\n347\t\n348\t6\n349\t6\n350\t7\n351\t7\n352\t8\n353\t8\n354\t\n355\tActed dialogues\n356\tYouTube\n357\tFriends TV show\n358\tTV shows\n359\tStudio-acted clips\n360\tYouTube videos\n361\t\n362\tSpEmoC (Ours)\n363\t\n364\t306,544 (raw),\n365\t30k (refined)\n366\t\n367\tV, A, T\n368\t\n369\t7\n370\t\n371\tMovies & TV series\n372\t\n373\t3\n374\t\n375\tSpEmoC Dataset Construction\n376\t\n377\tExisting multimodal emotion datasets are often limited in scale, synchronization,\n378\tand emotional diversity, which restricts the development of robust and generalizable models. Many datasets rely on short caption-based clips or controlled\n379\tacted expressions and fail to capture natural emotional interactions. They also\n380\texhibit strong class imbalance, with the neutral class dominating and minority\n381\temotions such as fear and disgust underrepresented. These limitations highlight\n382\tthe need for a larger, balanced dataset that better reflects emotional variability\n383\t\n384\t\fSpEmoC: A Balanced Speaker-Segment Multimodal Emotion Benchmark\n385\t\n386\t5\n387\t\n388\tacross practical conversational scenarios.\n389\tTo address these gaps, we introduce SpEmoC, a large-scale multimodal emotion\n390\trecognition dataset focused on speaking segments with synchronized video,\n391\taudio, and text. SpEmoC contains 30,000 refined clips curated from 306,544 raw\n392\tsegments collected from 3,100 English-language movies and TV series selected\n393\tfor their emotionally expressive dialogues. The dataset captures diverse genres\n394\t(e.g., drama, comedy, horror, romance, thriller), formats (color and black-andwhite), and environmental conditions, reflecting realistic emotional expressions\n395\twith temporally aligned multimodal signals. Each segment preserves authentic speech, facial expressions, and contextual dialogue while excluding dubbed\n396\tor subtitled content to maintain linguistic fidelity. Through targeted filtering\n397\tand refinement, SpEmoC achieves a balanced distribution across seven emotion\n398\tclasses (Figure 2). Table 2 summarizes the dataset characteristics, while Figure\n399\t3 illustrates its visual and emotional diversity. Additional details of the data\n400\tcuration pipeline are provided in the Supplementary Sec: 4 .\n401\t\n402\tFig. 3: Examples from SpEmoC showing variation in genre, lighting, color, and expression. Each row displays 8 sampled frames from a distinct clip.\n403\t\n404\t3.1 Data Collection and Processing Pipeline\n405\tWe develop a scalable multi-stage pipeline that converts long-form videos into\n406\tsynchronized video, audio, and text segments (Figure 4), ensuring temporal\n407\talignment and modality consistency. Let  \\mathcal {V} = \\{V_1, V_2, \\dots , V_{3100}\\}  be the set of\n408\tsource videos, each  V_k  with time duration \\geq 40  minutes. The stages are outlined\n409\tbelow.\n410\ta. Dialogue Segmentation: We use the Whisper ASR model [21] to transcribe\n411\teach video with word-level timestamps. A video clip segment  v_{k}^{i}  (i^{th} clip of video\n412\tV_k ) is retained if it (i) contains at least 12 words, ensuring sufficient linguistic and\n413\temotional context, and (ii) ends with terminal punctuation (., !, ?) to capture\n414\ta complete utterance. Each video  V_k  yields a set of segments  \\{v_{k}^{1}, v_{k}^{2}, \\dots , v_{k}^{m}\\} .\n415\tThe total number of extracted clips is:\n416\t  \\scriptsize N_{\\text {clips}} = \\sum _{k=1}^{N} \\sum _{i=1}^{m} 1 \\approx 306{,}544 \n417\t\n418\t(1)\n419\t\n420\twhere  m  is the number of valid clip segments in  V_k  and N = |\\mathcal {V}|. This segmentation ensures meaningful dialogue boundaries rather than arbitrary frame\n421\t\n422\t\f6\n423\t\n424\tS. Bano et al.\n425\t\n426\twindows.\n427\tThe extracted clips are short dialogue segments (typically 3-6 seconds) and therefore usually contain a single dominant speaker. During the human verification\n428\tstage, annotators review the visual, audio, and textual modalities jointly to determine the emotion expressed in the clip. We do not explicitly perform speaker\n429\tdiarization or active speaker detection; instead, the assigned label corresponds\n430\tto the dominant emotional expression within the speaking segment.\n431\tb. Multimodal Extraction: After segmentation, each valid clip  v_{k}^{i}  is decomposed into three aligned modalities:\n432\t– Visual: Video segment  v_{k}^{i}  from the same temporal window, containing number of frames  |v_{k}^{i}| = (t_{end}-t_{start}) \\times \\text {FPS} . This process yields approximately\n433\t30 million frames across all clips.\n434\t– Text: Transcript  \\mathcal {T}_{k}^{i}  of the corresponding  v_{k}^{i}  clip, obtained from Whisper.\n435\t– Audio: Waveform  \\mathcal {A}_{k}^{i}  of the corresponding  v_{k}^{i}  clip, cropped from the interval\n436\t[t_{\\text {start}}, t_{\\text {end}}], using FFmpeg (open-source toolkit) [9], Where tstart is start time\n437\tand tend is end time.\n438\t– Human and Face Detection: Human bodies and faces are detected in each\n439\tframe of v_{k}^{i} using YOLOv8 [26] to verify the presence of a visible person in\n440\tthe clip v_{k}^{i} .\n441\tc. Synchronization Check: Temporal alignment between modalities is verified\n442\tby comparing audio and video durations (timestamp consistency):\n443\t  \\scriptsize |\\text {Duration}(\\mathcal {A}_{k}^{i}) - (t_{end}(v_{k}^{i}) - t_{start}(v_{k}^{i})| \\leq \\epsilon \n444\t\n445\t(2)\n446\t\n447\tHere,  \\epsilon = 0.1~\\text {sec}  denotes the maximum allowable deviation. Segments violating this constraint are reprocessed or excluded.\n448\tOverall, this preprocessing pipeline, comprising segmentation, multimodal extraction, and synchronization followed by post-processing, produces a high-quality,\n449\ttemporally aligned clips for multimodal annotation and analysis.\n450\t3.2\n451\t\n452\tAnnotation Methodology\n453\t\n454\tWe adopt a hybrid annotation pipeline that integrates automated multimodal\n455\tlabeling with human validation and dataset refinement to ensure both scalability\n456\tand reliability. Pretrained emotion recognition models first generate automated\n457\tannotations across text and audio modalities, followed by systematic filtering\n458\tand expert validation to refine ambiguous or low-confidence samples. This design\n459\tbalances large-scale automation with human oversight, yielding a high-quality,\n460\tbalanced multimodal dataset.\n461\tEmotion Taxonomy: Following Ekman’s basic-emotion taxonomy [5], we adopt\n462\tseven discrete categories for cross-dataset comparability: E = {Anger, Disgust,\n463\tFear, Joy, Sadness, Surprise, Neutral}\n464\tDomain-specific pretrained models are used for text and audio, sharing identical\n465\temotion vocabularies to maintain cross-modal consistency.\n466\tAutomated Multimodal Annotation: Each dialogue transcript (Tki ) is analyzed using a fine-tuned DistilRoBERTa model [22]. For each utterance, we\n467\t\n468\t\fSpEmoC: A Balanced Speaker-Segment Multimodal Emotion Benchmark\n469\t\n470\t7\n471\t\n472\tTable 2: Overview of the Proposed Multimodal Emotion Recognition SpEmoC\n473\tDataset, Highlighting Source, Structure, Modalities, Annotation, Splitting policy, and\n474\tEmotion Coverage.\n475\tData Source and Composition\n476\tSource\n477\tNumber of Videos\n478\tVideo Length\n479\tVideo Types\n480\t\n481\tYouTube (Movies and TV Series)\n482\t3,100\n483\t≥ 40 minutes each\n484\tColor and Black-and-White , English language , Non-dubbing,\n485\tSubtitle independent\n486\tDrama, Comedy, Horror, Thriller, Romance, History, etc.\n487\t306,544\n488\t3–6 seconds\n489\t30 million+\n490\tSpeaking segments only\n491\t\n492\tVideo genres\n493\tTotal Number of Clips\n494\tAverage Clip Duration\n495\tTotal Frames\n496\tFocus Per Clip\n497\tModalities and Preprocessing\n498\tModalities\n499\tVideo, Audio, Text\n500\tFace/Human Detection\n501\tYOLOv8 [26]\n502\tFace Presence Threshold\n503\tFace detected in ≥ 90% of frames\n504\tAnnotation and Labeling Strategy\n505\tAnnotation Models\n506\tDistilRoBERTa (Text) [22], Wav2Vec 2.0 (Audio) [2]\n507\tLabel Type\n508\tSingle dominant emotion per clip\n509\tLabel Fusion\n510\tLogit-Based Fusion from Text and Audio modalities\n511\tDataset Spliting Strategy\n512\tMovie/franchise-level\n513\tAll clips from the same movie, sequel, or multi-episode series\n514\tare assigned exclusively to one split (train, validation, or test)\n515\tto ensure a fully unseen test set.\n516\tEmotion Classes\n517\tCategories\n518\tAnger, Disgust, Fear, Joy, Sadness, Surprise, Neutral\n519\t\n520\tobtain a vector of real-valued scores called sentiment logits, representing the\n521\tunnormalized model confidence for each emotion class in E.\n522\t  \\scriptsize {L_{t,}}_k^{i} = \\text {logits}_{\\text {text}}(\\mathcal {T}_{k}^{i}) \\in \\mathbb {R}^{|E|} \n523\t\n524\t(3)\n525\t\n526\twhere {L_{t,}}_k^{i} = [{l_{t,}}_{k,1}^{i}, \\dots , {l_{t,}}_{k,7}^{i}] contains model confidence scores for all emotion\n527\tclasses. Similarly, the corresponding acoustic segment \\protect \\mathcal  {A}_{k}^{i} is processed using a\n528\tpretrained Wav2Vec 2.0 model [2], yielding\n529\t  \\scriptsize {L_{a,}}_{k}^{i} = \\text {logits}_{\\text {audio}}(\\mathcal {A}_{k}^{i}) \\in \\mathbb {R}^{|E|} \n530\t\n531\t(4)\n532\t\n533\twhere {L_{a,}}_{k}^{i} = [{l_{a,}}_{k,1}^{i}, \\dots , {l_{a,}}_{k,7}^{i}] represents the audio-domain logits.\n534\tLogit-Based Multimodal Fusion for Emotion Labeling: The sentiment\n535\tlogits  L_{t}  and  L_{a} are used as inputs to our logit-based fusion mechanism to\n536\tgenerate consistent pseudo-labels without relying on the noisy visual modality.\n537\tInstead of using only top-class predictions, we leverage the full logit distributions\n538\tto capture richer emotion signals and uncertainty across modalities.\n539\tFor a fixed emotion label set  E = \\{e_1, \\dots , e_7\\} , each clip produces two 7dimensional logit vectors:  L_t = [l_{t,1}, \\dots , l_{t,7}]  from the text model and\n540\t L_a = [l_{a,1}, \\dots , l_{a,7}] \n541\tfrom the audio model, where the logits are unnormalized scores\n542\t l_{m,i} \\in \\mathbb {R}  with  m \\in \\{t, a\\} .\n543\tAssuming a uniform prior  P(e_i) = 1/|E| , the posterior over emotion class  e_i \n544\tis modeled as P(e_i | L_t, L_a) \\propto P(L_t | e_i) \\cdot P(L_a | e_i)\n545\twhere likelihoods are softmax-normalized:\n546\t  \\scriptsize \\tilde {P}_m(e_i) = \\frac {\\exp (l_{m,i})}{\\sum _{j=1}^{7} \\exp (l_{m,j})}, \\quad m \\in \\{t, a\\} \n547\t\n548\t(5)\n549\t\n550\t\f8\n551\t\n552\tS. Bano et al.\n553\t\n554\twhere l_{m,i} denotes the logit for class e_i from modality  m \\in \\{t, a\\} .To encourage modality agreement, we introduce a KL-divergence penalty:\n555\t(6)\n556\t\n557\t  \\scriptsize D_{\\text {KL}}(\\tilde {P}_t || \\tilde {P}_a) = \\sum _{i=1}^{7} \\tilde {P}_t(e_i) \\log \\left ( \\frac {\\tilde {P}_t(e_i)}{\\tilde {P}_a(e_i)} \\right ) \n558\t\n559\tThis yields a fused decision score:\n560\t  \\scriptsize S(e_i) = \\log \\tilde {P}_t(e_i) + \\log \\tilde {P}_a(e_i) - \\lambda D_{\\text {KL}}(\\tilde {P}_t || \\tilde {P}_a) \n561\t\n562\t(7)\n563\t\n564\twhere \\lambda = 0.5 controls the regularization strength. The predicted label and\n565\tconfidence are\n566\t  \\scriptsize e^* = \\arg \\max _{e_i \\in E} S(e_i) , \\quad F(e^*) = \\frac {1}{1 + \\exp (-S(e^*))}, \\quad F(e^*) \\in [0, 1] \n567\t\n568\t(8)\n569\t\n570\tThis formulation captures full distributional uncertainty from both modalities\n571\tand enforces semantic coherence between textual and acoustic cues. Unlike majority voting or hard max fusion, the KL divergence regularizer penalizes disagreements and rewards confident, aligned predictions.\n572\tWe further use the agreement condition  \\arg \\max L_t = \\arg \\max L_a  and confidence score  F(e^*)  to filter noisy labels. This approach scales efficiently across\n573\tlarge unlabeled datasets and acts as a pseudo-supervisor for high-quality emotion annotation. Figure 4 illustrates the automated construction and multimodal\n574\tlabeling pipeline of the SpEmoC dataset. Further information on the annotation\n575\tfile is provided in the Supplementary Sec: 5 .\n576\t\" You tell her you're\n577\ther mother, she'll just\n578\tgo away with you .\"\n579\t\n580\tAnnotation\n581\tMethodology\n582\t\n583\tData Processing\n584\t\n585\tExtracted Text :\n586\t\n587\tDialogue\n588\tSegmentation\n589\t\n590\tExtracted Audio :\n591\t\n592\tLogitBased\n593\tMultimodal\n594\tFusion\n595\t\n596\tMovies\n597\tFace Box\n598\tSpeaking Segment Clips\n599\t(Dialogue-based: 3-6 sec)\n600\t306,544\n601\t\n602\tYOLO v8\n603\tExtracted visual clips :\n604\t\n605\tFace Presence\n606\tVerification\n607\tFace detected ≥ 90% frames\n608\t\n609\tEmotion label\n610\tof 306,544\n611\tclips\n612\t\n613\tHuman Box\n614\t\n615\tFig. 4: SpEmoC construction and multimodal labeling pipeline. Movies are segmented\n616\tinto short dialogue-based clips (3-6 s), from which synchronized text, audio, and visual\n617\tstreams are extracted. Text and audio logits are fused to obtain clip-level emotion\n618\tlabels, while YOLOv8 verifies face presence in visual frames (≥ 90% frames).\n619\t\n620\t3.3\n621\t\n622\tDataset Refinement and Filtering\n623\t\n624\tThe initial 306,544 annotated clips exhibited a strong class imbalance dominated\n625\tby the neutral class (Figure 5), potentially biasing model training. To address\n626\tthis, we applied a multi-step filtering strategy using threshold-based constraints\n627\ton text and audio neutral scores, along with face-presence verification in visual frames, to retain emotionally expressive clips. Thresholds were determined\n628\tthrough manual experimentation and validated via performance analysis, revealing that many neutral clips contained weak emotional content reflected by high\n629\tneutral scores. Figure 1 illustrates the complete dataset refinement and human\n630\tannotation workflow. For a clip v_{k}^{i} ,\n631\t\n632\t\fSpEmoC: A Balanced Speaker-Segment Multimodal Emotion Benchmark\n633\t\n634\t9\n635\t\n636\t– {L_{t,}}_{k}^{i} = \\text {text\\_neutral\\_logit}(\\mathcal {T}_{k}^{i}): text neutrality logit\n637\t– {L_{a},}_k^i = \\text {audio\\_neutral\\_logit}(\\mathcal {A}_k^{i}): audio neutrality logit\n638\t– f_k^{i} = \\text {has\\_face}(v_k^{i}) \\in [0,1]: face-presence confidence in video frames\n639\tLogits are converted to probabilities via the sigmoid function:\n640\t  \\scriptsize {w_{t,}}_k^{i} = \\sigma ({L_{t,}}_{k}^{i}) = \\frac {1}{1 + e^{-{{L_{t,}}_{k}^{i}}}}, \\quad {w_{a,}}_k^i = \\sigma ({L_{a},}_k^i) = \\frac {1}{1 + e^{-{{L_{a},}_k^i}}} \n641\t\n642\tA clip v_k^{i} is retained if: fki ≥ θf , wt, ik < θt , wa, ik < θa\n643\twhere \\theta _f = 0.9 face presence in at least 90% of frames, and \\theta _t = \\theta _a = 0.05\n644\texclude weakly emotional (neutral) segments. A small portion of neutral clips\n645\t(\\sim 15\\%) is retained for balance. This filtering reduced the pool to 50,000 highquality clips with a significantly flatter class distribution.\n646\t\n647\t200000\n648\t\n649\t8000\n650\t\n651\t150000\n652\t\n653\t6000\n654\t\n655\t100000\n656\t\n657\t4000\n658\t\n659\t50000\n660\t\n661\t2000\n662\t\n663\t4373\n664\t\n665\t0\n666\t\n667\t0\n668\t\n669\tAnger\n670\t\n671\tDisgust\n672\t\n673\tFear\n674\t\n675\tJoy\n676\t\n677\tSadness Surprise\n678\t\n679\tNeutral\n680\t\n681\tAnger\n682\t\n683\tDisgust\n684\t\n685\tFear\n686\t\n687\tJoy\n688\t\n689\tSadness Surprise\n690\t\n691\tNeutral\n692\t\n693\tFig. 5: Emotion class distribution before (blue) and after filtering (green). The initial\n694\t306K clips were dominated by the neutral class, while fear was underrepresented. A\n695\ttwo-step filtering process was applied: threshold-based filtering, followed by human\n696\tvalidation to remove ambiguous samples. The resulting 30,000-clip dataset achieves a\n697\tmore balanced distribution across all seven emotion classes.\n698\t\n699\tHuman Validation of Labels: Following automatic filtering, 50,000 clips were\n700\tsubjected to human verification. Twenty expert annotators, proficient in English\n701\tand trained under standardized Ekman-based guidelines [5], evaluated each clip\n702\tusing all three modalities (text, audio, visual). Each sample was independently\n703\tannotated by at least three experts, and final labels were determined through\n704\tmajority voting. Annotators did not have access to model-predicted labels during\n705\tthis process. Inter-annotator agreement reached Fleiss’ \\kappa = 0.62 (substantial\n706\tagreement [12]). Ambiguous or inconsistent clips were discarded, resulting in\n707\t30,000 refined samples that maintain balance across all seven emotions.\n708\tSpEmoC Demographics: This section summarizes the demographic composition of the dataset (30K refined clips) across age, gender, and ethnicity. As\n709\tshown in Figure 6, the dataset spans a wide age range from children to seniors\n710\tand includes both male and female participants from multiple ethnic groups.\n711\tAfter dataset refinement, demographic attributes (age group, gender, ethnicity) were estimated using a pretrained visual demographic model and verified\n712\tthrough manual cross-checking. Since these attributes are inferred from visual\n713\tcontent in movie clips, they remain approximate and may be affected by factors\n714\tsuch as makeup, lighting, or role-based appearance changes.\n715\tDataset Splitting Strategy: To prevent content leakage, we adopt a movielevel split assigning complete movies to train (70%), validation (10%), or test\n716\t\n717\t\fS. Bano et al.\n718\t(a) Age Distribution\n719\t\n720\t50\n721\t\n722\t44.88%\n723\t\n724\tPercentage (%)\n725\t\n726\t40\n727\t\n728\t70\n729\t\n730\t40.84%\n731\t\n732\t60\n733\t\n734\t30\n735\t20\n736\t11.89%\n737\t\n738\t10\n739\t0\n740\t\n741\t0.79%\n742\tChild\n743\t\n744\t1.58%\n745\tTeen Young Adult Adult\n746\t\n747\tAge Group\n748\t\n749\tPercentage (%)\n750\t\n751\t10\n752\t\n753\t(b) Ethnic Distribution\n754\t62.11%\n755\t\n756\t50\n757\t\n758\t31.60%\n759\tFemale\n760\t\n761\t40\n762\t30\n763\t\n764\t27.87%\n765\t68.40%\n766\tMale\n767\t\n768\t20\n769\t10\n770\t\n771\tSenior\n772\t\n773\t(c) Gender Distribution\n774\t\n775\t0 Western\n776\t\n777\t6.66%\n778\tAfrican\n779\t\n780\t3.36%\n781\tAsian Middle Eastern\n782\t\n783\tFig. 6: Demographic distribution of the SpEmoC dataset across age groups, ethnicity,\n784\tand gender, illustrating its diversity and balanced population coverage.\n785\t\n786\t(20%) sets. This ensures no overlap in scenes, actors, or dialogues between splits,\n787\tenabling robust real-world evaluation. This movie-independent split ensures all\n788\trelated sequels or series episodes remain within a single set, preventing actor\n789\tor scene overlap and enabling robust real-world generalization and guaranteeing an unseen test set. The final dataset statistics and class-wise distributions\n790\tare compared against MELD and CAER in Figure 2(a) and Table 3 detailing\n791\tclass distributions across splits. The dataset split information is provided in the\n792\tSupplementary Sec: 7. Overall, this annotation-refinement pipeline integrates\n793\tmultimodal fusion, threshold-based filtering, and expert validation to produce a\n794\tbalanced, trustworthy dataset suitable for fair multimodal emotion recognition.\n795\tTable 3: Comparison of emotion class distributions across training, validation, and\n796\ttest splits for MELD [20], CAER [13], and the proposed SpEmoC dataset. Red indicates\n797\tunderrepresented classes (e.g., Disgust, Fear), while Blue denotes the overrepresented\n798\tNeutral class in existing datasets.\n799\tMELD\n800\tCAER\n801\tSpEmoC (Ours)\n802\tCategories\n803\tTrain Val Test Train Val Test Train Val Test\n804\tAnger\n805\t1109 153 345 1136 162 325 3980 392 1271\n806\tDisgust\n807\t271 22 68 500 71 145 4946 551 1298\n808\t268 40 50 358 51 102 2378 226\n809\t729\n810\tFear\n811\tJoy\n812\t1743 163 402 1905 272 544 2506 340\n813\t578\n814\tNeutral\n815\t4710 470 1256 3202 457 915 2804 320\n816\t895\n817\tSadness\n818\t683 111 208 1028 146 294 1612 195\n819\t474\n820\t1205 150 281 1093 157 315 3181 376\n821\t811\n822\tSurprise\n823\t\n824\tEthical Considerations: We prioritize copyright and responsible use in constructing SpEmoC. The dataset is derived from publicly available movies and TV\n825\tseries and will be released strictly under fair-use provisions for non-commercial\n826\tresearch. Access will be regulated through an End User License Agreement\n827\t(EULA), requiring researchers to apply for access and comply with clearly defined terms. To ensure transparency, the dataset repository will provide detailed\n828\tdocumentation on usage boundaries, licensing conditions, and ethical safeguards.\n829\t\n830\t4\n831\t\n832\tBenchmarking and Analysis of SpEmoC\n833\t\n834\tTo ensure fair evaluation of SpEmoC, all experiments use identical training\n835\tprotocols, optimization settings, and metrics across MELD, CAER, and SpEmoC. We benchmark five multimodal emotion recognition models MulT [25],\n836\t\n837\t\fSpEmoC: A Balanced Speaker-Segment Multimodal Emotion Benchmark\n838\t\n839\t11\n840\t\n841\tMISA [11], EmotionCLIP [30], TCL-MAP [32], and EMOE [7] using consistent\n842\t70/10/20 source-level splits.\n843\tThe evaluation covers five aspects: in-domain benchmarking, cross-dataset generalization, low-data transfer learning, neutral-class removal analysis, and modalitylevel transfer. Performance is reported using Weighted F1, Macro-F1, per-class\n844\tF1 and imbalance gap ∆ = W-F1−Macro-F1. Additional implementation details\n845\tare provided in the Supplementary Sec: 3 .\n846\t4.1\n847\t\n848\tIn-Domain Benchmarking on SpEmoC\n849\t\n850\tWe evaluate five representative multimodal emotion recognition models on SpEmoC and compare them with two widely used benchmarks, MELD and CAER.\n851\tWhile W-F1 reflects overall accuracy, Macro-F1 measures balanced performance\n852\tacross emotion classes, and ∆ quantifies bias toward majority categories. Table 4 shows that all models achieve substantially higher Macro-F1 on SpEmoC\n853\tthan on MELD and CAER, with improvements exceeding 30 absolute points on\n854\taverage. For instance, EMOE improves from 38.19 (MELD) and 15.54 (CAER)\n855\tto 70.25 on SpEmoC, while TCL-MAP increases from 45.46 and 20.99 to 73.34.\n856\tSimilar gains are observed for MulT, MISA, and EmotionCLIP, indicating that\n857\tthe improvements arise from the dataset design rather than model architecture.\n858\tA key observation is the dramatic reduction of the imbalance gap (∆). On MELD\n859\tand CAER the gap typically ranges between 15-25 points, reflecting strong bias\n860\ttoward dominant classes such as Neutral. In contrast, SpEmoC consistently produces near-zero imbalance gaps (∆ ≤ 0.65), indicating much more uniform performance across the seven emotion categories. Per-class analysis further confirms\n861\tthis trend. Minority emotions such as Fear and Disgust, which often obtain nearzero F1 scores on MELD and CAER, achieve substantially higher performance\n862\ton SpEmoC (typically 36-71 F1). These results demonstrate that the balanced\n863\temotion distribution. SpEmoC provide stronger supervision signals for multimodal emotion learning. The consistent gains across architectures indicate that\n864\tSpEmoC mitigates class imbalance and provides a reliable benchmark for multimodal emotion recognition.\n865\tTable 4: In-Domain Per-Class Performance and Imbalance Analysis Across SpEmoC,\n866\tMELD, and CAER. Lower imbalance gap (∆) indicates better class balance. Bold: Best\n867\tMethods\n868\t\n869\tDataset Surprise Joy Fear Disgust Anger Neutral Sadness W-F1 ↑ Macro-F1↑ ∆(Gap↓)\n870\tMELD\n871\t13.30 18.93 0.74\n872\t0.0\n873\t23.52\n874\t37.95\n875\t14.33\n876\t25.09\n877\t18.61\n878\t6.48\n879\tMISA [11]\n880\tCAER\n881\t18.72 58.08 0.0\n882\t15.71 17.80\n883\t49.33\n884\t21.92\n885\t32.82\n886\t25.94\n887\t6.88\n888\tSpEmoC 41.30 66.40 36.00 49.80 50.90\n889\t32.40\n890\t51.70\n891\t50.78\n892\t47.50\n893\t3.28\n894\tMELD\n895\t26.28 39.72 0.0\n896\t0.0\n897\t28.44\n898\t58.63\n899\t17.21\n900\t34.59\n901\t24.33\n902\t10.26\n903\tEmotionCLIP [30] CAER\n904\t11.94 34.88 0.0\n905\t0.0\n906\t21.37\n907\t46.52\n908\t13.76\n909\t27.45\n910\t18.35\n911\t9.10\n912\tSpEmoC 52.63 66.93 50.49 55.82 51.60\n913\t31.76\n914\t48.47\n915\t51.30\n916\t49.50\n917\t1.8\n918\tMELD\n919\t56.04 56.44 17.07 22.22 46.05\n920\t77.75\n921\t33.93\n922\t62.68\n923\t45.46\n924\t17.22\n925\tTCL-MAP [32]\n926\tCAER\n927\t13.24 28.73 10.85 7.51\n928\t23.37\n929\t44.79\n930\t12.98\n931\t28.26\n932\t20.99\n933\t7.27\n934\tSpEmoC 74.36 75.55 71.13 70.84 73.76\n935\t75.51\n936\t72.25\n937\t73.67\n938\t73.34\n939\t0.33\n940\tMELD\n941\t54.59 54.55 6.06\n942\t6.38\n943\t43.95\n944\t73.86\n945\t27.92\n946\t59.04\n947\t38.19\n948\t20.85\n949\tEMOE [7]\n950\tCAER\n951\t0.0\n952\t28.66 0.0\n953\t0.0\n954\t24.34\n955\t51.95\n956\t3.82\n957\t36.52\n958\t15.54\n959\t20.98\n960\tSpEmoC 80.94 84.73 66.42 66.78 65.85\n961\t61.01\n962\t66.05\n963\t70.30\n964\t70.25\n965\t0.05\n966\tMulT [25]\n967\t\n968\tMELD\n969\tCAER\n970\tSpEmoC\n971\t\n972\t49.74\n973\t9.84\n974\t47.10\n975\t\n976\t55.42 7.27\n977\t22.99 0.0\n978\t75.26 40.44\n979\t\n980\t9.09\n981\t0.0\n982\t60.06\n983\t\n984\t42.46\n985\t4.02\n986\t60.05\n987\t\n988\t74.08\n989\t52.16\n990\t35.13\n991\t\n992\t32.42\n993\t0.0\n994\t60.47\n995\t\n996\t58.85\n997\t36.03\n998\t53.37\n999\t\n1000\t38.64\n1001\t12.72\n1002\t52.72\n1003\t\n1004\t20.21\n1005\t23.31\n1006\t0.65\n1007\t\n1008\t\f12\n1009\t\n1010\t4.2\n1011\t\n1012\tS. Bano et al.\n1013\t\n1014\tCross-Dataset Generalization Analysis\n1015\t\n1016\tTo measure transfer robustness, we perform direct cross-dataset evaluation each\n1017\tmodel is trained on one dataset and tested on the others without adaptation\n1018\t(Tables 5–8).\n1019\tOverall trend: Across TCL-MAP, EMOE, MulT, and MISA, training on SpEmoC yields more balanced class-wise performance and improved robustness to\n1020\tclass imbalance than training on MELD or CAER. While MELD↔CAER transfers are often stronger than transfers involving SpEmoC (reflecting their closer\n1021\tdistributional similarity and shared Neutral-dominant bias), SpEmoC-trained\n1022\tmodels degrade more gracefully across transfer directions and avoid brittle failures.\n1023\tMinority-class stability: The main difference appears in rare emotions. When\n1024\ttrained on MELD/CAER, models frequently collapse on Fear and Disgust under\n1025\ttransfer (near-zero F1 in several directions; e.g., MulT Table/MISA tables 7 and\n1026\t6). In contrast, SpEmoC-trained models retain non-trivial F1 for these classes\n1027\tacross architectures, indicating improved minority-emotion generalization rather\n1028\tthan overfitting to Neutral.\n1029\tDataset Similarity (MELD vs CAER): MELD and CAER show stronger\n1030\tmutual transfer than transfers involving SpEmoC (Tables 5–6; e.g., TCL-MAP:\n1031\t64.21 W-F1, EMOE: 35.61 W-F1), indicating closer distributions and Neutralclass bias compared to the more balanced SpEmoC.\n1032\tModel-Agnostic Consistency: Improvements are consistent across architectures (TCL-MAP, MulT, MISA, EMOE; Tables 5–6), suggesting that the observed improvements are associated with SpEmoC’s overall dataset design rather\n1033\tthan model-specific factors.\n1034\tImbalance-gap interpretation: Consistent with the above, MELD/CAER\n1035\ttraining produces large imbalance gaps (∆ = 15-27; Tables 5–6), indicating\n1036\tstrong bias toward the Neutral class. In contrast, SpEmoC training yields much\n1037\tsmaller gaps across architectures-TCL-MAP (∆ = 0.33, Table 5), EMOE (∆ =\n1038\t0.34, Table 8), MulT (∆ = 0.65, Table 7), and MISA (∆ = 3.28, Table 6)\n1039\treflecting more balanced class-wise recognition.\n1040\tConnection to downstream results: These findings help explain why SpEmoC pretraining improves (i) fine-tuning on MELD/CAER (Table 10) and (ii)\n1041\tlow-data adaptation (Table 9), balanced supervision in SpEmoC preserves discriminative features for minority emotions, which remain useful under domain\n1042\tshift and limited supervision.\n1043\tTable 5: Cross-dataset generalization across SpEmoC (ours), MELD, and CAER using the TCL-MAP [32] model, showing more balanced performance when trained on\n1044\tSpEmoC.\n1045\tTrain → Test\n1046\t\n1047\tSurprise Joy Fear Disgust Anger Neutral Sadness W-F1 ↑ Macro-F1 ↑ ∆(Gap↓)\n1048\t\n1049\tCAER → CAER\n1050\tCAER → MELD\n1051\tCAER → SpEmoC(ours)\n1052\t\n1053\t13.24\n1054\t19.46\n1055\t21.14\n1056\t\n1057\t28.73 10.85\n1058\t17.44 5.13\n1059\t34.79 3.49\n1060\t\n1061\t7.51\n1062\t1.14\n1063\t5.47\n1064\t\n1065\t23.37\n1066\t16.09\n1067\t40.94\n1068\t\n1069\t44.79\n1070\t50.71\n1071\t25.89\n1072\t\n1073\t12.98\n1074\t13.56\n1075\t17.07\n1076\t\n1077\t28.26\n1078\t34.62\n1079\t24.64\n1080\t\n1081\t20.21\n1082\t17.65\n1083\t19.83\n1084\t\n1085\t8.05\n1086\t16.97\n1087\t4.81\n1088\t\n1089\tMELD → CAER\n1090\tMELD → MELD\n1091\tMELD → SpEmoC(ours)\n1