34.33\n1531\t71.44\n1532\t\n1533\t45.88\n1534\t65.50\n1535\t62.25\n1536\t\n1537\t11.11\n1538\t23.61\n1539\t66.05\n1540\t\n1541\t30.83\n1542\t47.74\n1543\t71.85\n1544\t\n1545\t19.56\n1546\t29.97\n1547\t72.19\n1548\t\n1549\t11.27\n1550\t17.77\n1551\t0.34\n1552\t\n1553\tComprehensive Dataset Analysis\n1554\t\n1555\tWe conduct a series of comprehensive analyses to evaluate the robustness, generalization, and practical utility of the proposed SpEmoC dataset. Rather than\n1556\tfocusing on architectural novelty, we systematically analyze the impact of dataset\n1557\tdesign choices across datasets, modalities, data availability, and class balance using standard multimodal emotion recognition frameworks. All experiments are\n1558\tconducted using the EMOE [7] model under identical training settings.\n1559\tLow-Data Transfer Learning Performance: We evaluate fine-tuning on\n1560\tMELD and CAER using 10%, 30%, and 50% of training data (Table 9). SpEmoCpretrained models consistently outperform non-pretrained baselines, with the\n1561\tlargest gains in the extreme low-data regime (10%). This indicates that SpEmoC provides transferable emotional representations that remain effective under\n1562\tlimited supervision.\n1563\tCross-dataset transfer learning: Table 10 shows that SpEmoC pretraining consistently improves cross-dataset performance. On MELD, minority-class\n1564\t\n1565\t\f14\n1566\t\n1567\tS. Bano et al.\n1568\t\n1569\tTable 9: Low-data transfer learning results when fine-tuning on MELD and CAER\n1570\tusing only 10%, 30%, and 50% of the training data. SpEmoC pretraining consistently\n1571\timproves performance across all data regimes.\n1572\tTraining Split Baseline\n1573\t10%\n1574\t30%\n1575\t50%\n1576\t\n1577\t+SpEmoC Pretraining (W-F1 ↑ )\n1578\t\n1579\tMacro-F1↑\n1580\t\n1581\t∆(Gap↓)\n1582\t\n1583\t59.16 / 34.70\n1584\t62.40 / 35.34\n1585\t61.50 / 35.61\n1586\t\n1587\t34 .60/15.40\n1588\t35.77/14.48\n1589\t38.04/11.66\n1590\t\n1591\t24.46/19.30\n1592\t23.64/20.86\n1593\t22.99/23.95\n1594\t\n1595\t57.13 / 31.40\n1596\t61.00 / 35.27\n1597\t59.73 / 34.89\n1598\t\n1599\trecognition improves substantially, particularly for Fear (6.06 → 16.33) and Disgust (6.38 → 17.65), increasing W-F1 from 59.04 to 63.26 (+4.22). On CAER,\n1600\tgains in Surprise, Disgust, and Sadness raise W-F1 from 36.52 to 38.16 (+1.64).\n1601\tReverse transfer experiments further show consistent improvements when SpEmoC is finetuned from MELD or CAER initialization, confirming the robustness\n1602\tof cross-dataset representations.\n1603\tFurther analyses on backbone variants and neutral-class removal are provided\n1604\tin the Supplementary Sec: 1 and 2.\n1605\tTable 10: Class-wise and W-F1 improvements after SpEmoC pretraining on MELD\n1606\tand CAER. ∆ denotes relative gain.\n1607\tDataset\n1608\t\n1609\tSurprise Joy Fear Disgust Anger Neutral Sadness Micro-F1 ↑ W-F1 ↑ ∆ (gain)\n1610\t\n1611\tMELD Training\n1612\tMELD Finetuning (+SpEmoC Pretraining)\n1613\t\n1614\t54.59\n1615\t58.22\n1616\t\n1617\t54.55 6.06\n1618\t6.38\n1619\t55.20 16.33 17.65\n1620\t\n1621\t43.95\n1622\t41.68\n1623\t\n1624\t73.86\n1625\t78.39\n1626\t\n1627\t27.92\n1628\t21.90\n1629\t\n1630\t38.19\n1631\t41.34\n1632\t\n1633\t59.04\n1634\t63.26\n1635\t\n1636\t+ 4.22\n1637\t\n1638\tSpEmoC Training\n1639\tSpEmoC Finetuning (+MELD Pretraining)\n1640\t\n1641\t80.94\n1642\t80.65\n1643\t\n1644\t84.73 66.42\n1645\t85.08 68.11\n1646\t\n1647\t66.78\n1648\t71.32\n1649\t\n1650\t65.85\n1651\t70.51\n1652\t\n1653\t61.01\n1654\t61.93\n1655\t\n1656\t66.05\n1657\t66.73\n1658\t\n1659\t70.25\n1660\t71.16\n1661\t\n1662\t70.30\n1663\t71.47\n1664\t\n1665\t+1.17\n1666\t\n1667\tCAER Training\n1668\tCAER Finetuning (+SpEmoC Pretraining)\n1669\t\n1670\t0.0\n1671\t13.92\n1672\t\n1673\t28.66\n1674\t26.98\n1675\t\n1676\t0.0\n1677\t0.0\n1678\t\n1679\t0.0\n1680\t2.3\n1681\t\n1682\t24.34\n1683\t23.35\n1684\t\n1685\t51.95\n1686\t52.47\n1687\t\n1688\t3.82\n1689\t10.70\n1690\t\n1691\t15.64\n1692\t19.81\n1693\t\n1694\t36.52\n1695\t38.16\n1696\t\n1697\t+1.64\n1698\t\n1699\tSpEmoC Training\n1700\tSpEmoC Finetuning (+CAER Pretraining)\n1701\t\n1702\t80.94\n1703\t79.92\n1704\t\n1705\t84.73 66.42\n1706\t84.08 68.30\n1707\t\n1708\t66.78\n1709\t71.41\n1710\t\n1711\t65.85\n1712\t72.41\n1713\t\n1714\t61.01\n1715\t62.55\n1716\t\n1717\t66.05\n1718\t66.67\n1719\t\n1720\t70.25\n1721\t71.34\n1722\t\n1723\t70.30\n1724\t71.84\n1725\t\n1726\t+1.54\n1727\t\n1728\t5\n1729\t\n1730\tConclusion and Future Work\n1731\t\n1732\tWe introduced SpEmoC, a large-scale multimodal emotion recognition benchmark containing 30,000 high-quality clips curated from 306,544 speaking segments across 3,100 English-language movies and TV series. Constructed through\n1733\ta hybrid pipeline combining pretrained models (DistilRoBERTa, Wav2Vec 2.0,\n1734\tYOLOv8), systematic filtering, and human validation, SpEmoC provides synchronized text, audio, and visual modalities with a near-balanced distribution\n1735\tacross seven emotions. By organizing samples around short dialogue-centered\n1736\tsegments and enforcing strict movie/series-level splits, the dataset mitigates class\n1737\timbalance, improves multimodal alignment, and prevents content leakage across\n1738\tsplits. Extensive experiments across multiple multimodal frameworks demonstrate improved cross-dataset generalization to MELD and CAER, stronger\n1739\trecognition of minority emotions such as fear and disgust, and substantially reduced imbalance gaps. Furthermore, SpEmoC pretraining consistently improves\n1740\tperformance in both fine-tuning and low-data settings, highlighting the importance of balanced dataset design for robust multimodal emotion recognition.\n1741\tFuture work includes extending SpEmoC with fine-grained, continuous, multilabel, intensity-based, and LLM-assisted affect annotations. We also plan to\n1742\timprove cultural and demographic diversity, multilingual coverage, metadata\n1743\trichness, and spontaneous conversational content to support fairer and more\n1744\trealistic emotion recognition.\n1745\t\n1746\t\fSpEmoC: A Balanced Speaker-Segment Multimodal Emotion Benchmark\n1747\t\n1748\t15\n1749\t\n1750\tReferences\n1751\t1. Albanie, S., Nagrani, A., Vedaldi, A., Zisserman, A.: Emotion recognition in speech\n1752\tusing cross-modal transfer in the wild. In: Proceedings of the 26th ACM international conference on Multimedia. pp. 292–301 (2018)\n1753\t2. Baevski, A., Zhou, Y., Mohamed, A., Auli, M.: wav2vec 2.0: A framework for\n1754\tself-supervised learning of speech representations. Advances in neural information\n1755\tprocessing systems 33, 12449–12460 (2020)\n1756\t3. Busso, C., Bulut, M., Lee, C.C., Kazemzadeh, A., Mower, E., Kim, S., Chang, J.N.,\n1757\tLee, S., Narayanan, S.S.: Iemocap: Interactive emotional dyadic motion capture\n1758\tdatabase. Language resources and evaluation 42, 335–359 (2008)\n1759\t4. Cheng, Z., Cheng, Z.Q., He, J.Y., Wang, K., Lin, Y., Lian, Z., Peng, X., Hauptmann, A.: Emotion-llama: Multimodal emotion recognition and reasoning with instruction tuning. Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems 37, 110805–\n1760\t110853 (2024)\n1761\t5. Ekman, P.: An argument for basic emotions. Cognition & emotion 6(3-4), 169–200\n1762\t(1992)\n1763\t6. El Ayadi, M., Kamel, M.S., Karray, F.: Survey on speech emotion recognition:\n1764\tFeatures, classification schemes, and databases. Pattern recognition 44(3), 572–\n1765\t587 (2011)\n1766\t7. Fang, Y., Huang, W., Wan, G., Su, K., Ye, M.: Emoe: Modality-specific enhanced\n1767\tdynamic emotion experts. In: Proceedings of the Computer Vision and Pattern\n1768\tRecognition Conference. pp. 14314–14324 (2025)\n1769\t8. Feng, S., Lubis, N., Geishauser, C., Lin, H.c., Heck, M., van Niekerk, C., Gasic, M.:\n1770\tEmowoz: A large-scale corpus and labelling scheme for emotion recognition in taskoriented dialogue systems. In: Proceedings of the Thirteenth Language Resources\n1771\tand Evaluation Conference. pp. 4096–4113 (2022)\n1772\t9. F